<!-- HERO -->
<header class="hero">
  <div class="hero-inner">
    <div class="brand-label">The Citizen Â· Civic Explainer Series</div>
    <h1><span>Capital Improvement Plans</span><br>Explained Visually</h1>
    <p class="hero-sub">How your city plans, funds, and builds the infrastructure you depend on â€” and how you can hold them accountable.</p>
  </div>
</header>

<div class="main">

  <!-- INTRO -->
  <section class="intro-section">
    <div class="intro-card">
      <h2>What Is a CIP?</h2>
      <p>A Capital Improvement Plan is a municipality's multi-year blueprint for building and maintaining major public infrastructure. It outlines which projects get built, when, and how they're funded â€” typically spanning 5 to 10 years with annual updates.</p>
      <p style="margin-top: 0.7rem;">Unlike annual operating budgets that cover day-to-day expenses, CIPs focus on big-ticket items: roads, water systems, parks, and public buildings that shape a community for decades.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="key-facts">
      <div class="fact">
        <div class="fact-icon">$</div>
        <div class="fact-text"><strong>Threshold</strong>Projects typically cost $50,000+ and have a useful life of 5+ years to qualify for CIP inclusion.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="fact">
        <div class="fact-icon">5Y</div>
        <div class="fact-text"><strong>Planning Horizon</strong>Most Texas cities use a 5-year rolling plan, updated annually as part of the budget process.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="fact">
        <div class="fact-icon">TX</div>
        <div class="fact-text"><strong>Texas Context</strong>Not legally required by state law, but considered best practice. Many growing cities use CIPs to justify bond elections.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="fact">
        <div class="fact-icon">ðŸ“‹</div>
        <div class="fact-text"><strong>Public Record</strong>CIP documents are public records. You have every right to request and review them under the Texas Public Information Act.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- TIMELINE -->
  <section class="timeline-section">
    <div class="section-header">
      <h2>The CIP Lifecycle</h2>
      <p>From needs assessment to ribbon-cutting â€” how a capital project moves through the pipeline</p>
    </div>
    <div class="timeline">
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-dot"></div>
        <div class="timeline-content">
          <div class="timeline-phase">Phase 1</div>
          <div class="timeline-title">Needs Assessment & Prioritization</div>
          <div class="timeline-desc">City departments submit project requests based on infrastructure condition reports, growth projections, and citizen complaints. Staff and council rank projects by urgency, safety, and strategic alignment.</div>
          <span class="timeline-months">Months 1â€“3</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-dot"></div>
        <div class="timeline-content">
          <div class="timeline-phase">Phase 2</div>
          <div class="timeline-title">Cost Estimation & Funding Strategy</div>
          <div class="timeline-desc">Engineers develop preliminary cost estimates. Finance staff identify funding sources â€” bonds, grants, impact fees, or general revenue. This is where the real fiscal commitments take shape.</div>
          <span class="timeline-months">Months 3â€“5</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-dot"></div>
        <div class="timeline-content">
          <div class="timeline-phase">Phase 3</div>
          <div class="timeline-title">Public Input & Council Review</div>
          <div class="timeline-desc">Draft CIP presented to the public for comment at hearings or workshops. Council reviews priorities, debates trade-offs, and may adjust project rankings. This is your best window to speak up.</div>
          <span class="timeline-months">Months 5â€“7</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-dot"></div>
        <div class="timeline-content">
          <div class="timeline-phase">Phase 4</div>
          <div class="timeline-title">Adoption & Budget Integration</div>
          <div class="timeline-desc">Council formally adopts the CIP, usually alongside the annual budget. Year 1 projects are funded and authorized. Years 2â€“5 remain planned but subject to future appropriation.</div>
          <span class="timeline-months">Months 7â€“9</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-dot"></div>
        <div class="timeline-content">
          <div class="timeline-phase">Phase 5</div>
          <div class="timeline-title">Design, Bid & Construction</div>
          <div class="timeline-desc">Funded projects move into detailed engineering design, competitive bidding, and construction. Timelines vary widely â€” a road project may take 2â€“4 years from design to completion.</div>
          <span class="timeline-months">Months 9â€“36+</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-dot"></div>
        <div class="timeline-content">
          <div class="timeline-phase">Phase 6</div>
          <div class="timeline-title">Monitoring & Annual Update</div>
          <div class="timeline-desc">Staff track project costs, timelines, and scope changes. The entire CIP is updated annually â€” projects can be added, delayed, or removed. Watch for projects that quietly slip year after year.</div>
          <span class="timeline-months">Ongoing / Annual</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

